>tend to suffer from diminishing returns
it depends on the sitcom
my opinion is sitcoms work better with an ensemble of 4-9 characters than when you have two leads, a sidekick or two, and a few occasional guest stars
you tell a few funny stories, and 2-3 times a season you move the character development bar; if you can't tell the seasons apart you either have a normie longrunner or it's at the frayed ends of the creative team
even better is when shows reference themselves, so events from earlier in the season or 2-3 years back all of a sudden get built on
As I said, moving that conflict bar means you can tell the same jokes in a different light
But there's only so many times (if you're not the Simpsons) that you can say clueless guy/weary wife/pain-in-the-ass kid/too-smart kid/bad boss/nosy neighbor or play the plots of fml/noodle incident/bills to pay/slice-of-life wankfest
